data.casing#Casing:
Controls the casing with which functions and parameters will generate.
Type	Default	Options	Function	Pascal	Camel, Pascal, Snake	Parameter	Snake	Camel, Pascal, Snake	
option Casing = {
    Function = Camel,
    Parameter = Pascal
}

data.defining-systems#Defining Systems:
You can define a system using the system keyword followed by the system name and its configuration block.
system PoisonHurts = {
    Query = {mut:Health}
    With = {IsPoisoned}
    Phase = Update
}

data.immutable-queries#Immutable Queries:
By default, components in a query are accessed immutably — the system can read their values but cannot modify them.
Query = {Health, Position}
In this example, the system runs on all entities that have both Health and Position, but neither can be changed.

data.mutable-queries#Mutable Queries:
To modify a component, you must explicitly mark it with the mut: prefix. You can freely mix mutable and immutable components in the same query.
Query = {mut:Health, Position}
Here, Health can be modified, while Position is read-only.

data.combining-filters#Combining Filters:
With and Without can be used together for precise control over which entities a system targets:
system PoisonHurts = {
    Query = {mut:Health}
    With = {IsPoisoned}
    Without = {IsDead}
    Phase = Update
}

data.priority#Priority:
Priority controls the order in which systems within the same phase execute. A lower number runs first, and a higher number runs later. If no priority is specified, systems run in the order they were declared.
RunFirst = {
    Query = {MyComponent},
    Phase = Update,
    Priority = 1
}
 
RunLast = {
    Query = {MyComponent},
    Phase = Update,
    Priority = 2
}
In this example, RunFirst executes before RunLast because it has a lower priority value.

data.maps#Maps:
Maps are key-value pair tables that have keys of one type, and values of the same or different type.
They can be defined using the map type. For example, a map of string keys and f64 values would look like:
map StringToNumber = {[string]: f64}

data.generics#Generics:
Maps support the use of generics. Generics can be a powerful tool for code reuse. For example a map template can be defined as:
map Map<K, V> = {[K]: V}
map StringToNumber = Map<[string], f64>

data.sets#Sets:
Sets are a map of static string keys to true. They can be defined using the set type. For example, a set of feature flags would look like:
set Flags = {
    FeatureA,
    FeatureB,
    FeatureC
}

data.unit-enums#Unit Enums:
Unit enums represent a set of possible values
They are defined using the enum type. For example a unit enum representing the state of a character:
enum CharacterStatus = {Idling, Walking, Running, Jumping, Falling}

data.tagged-enums#Tagged Enums:
Tagged enums are a set of possible variants, each with some data attached.
They can be defined using the enum type, then a string which is used for the tag field name, followed by the variants.
Each variant is defined by a tag, followed by a struct. Variants are separated by a comma.
enum MouseEvent = "Type" {
    Move = {
        Delta: vector,
        Position: vector,
    },
    Drag = {
        Delta: vector,
        Position: vector,
    },
    Click = {
        Buttom: enum {Left, Right, Middle}
        Position: vector
    }
}
Tagged enums are a very powerful way to represent many different types of data.
While not supported by the compiler, a union type can be substituted using tagged enums:
enum Union = "Type" {
    Number = {
        Value: f64
    },
    String = {
        Value: string
    }
}
This would result in the following Luau type:
type Union =
    | {Type: "Number", Value: number}
    | {Type: "String", Value: string}

data.generics-1#Generics:
Like maps, tagged enums also support generics.
For example, a tagged enum union template can be defined as:
enum Union<A, B> = "Type" {
    A = {
        Value: A
    },
    B = {
        Value: B
    }
}
 
enum NumberStringUnion = Union<f64, string>
